  "articleSummary": "This tutorial argues that self-hosting Docker services places full security responsibility on the user, covering both home networks and VPS providers like Vultr or AWS. Key points include avoiding the risky `:latest` tag by pinning versions and using automated update tools (Dependabot/Renovate), and never hard-coding secrets—instead using `.env`, Docker secrets, or external managers like HashiCorp Vault. The tone is instructive and practical, with recurring metaphors like “The `:latest` Dance” to frame update risks, and it includes code examples for validation and secret generation. The intended audience is self-hosters and hobbyists seeking actionable, layered security tips from basic to advanced.",
